### Tariana
Tariana is blahblahblah Vaupes, Tucano, blah

Tariana is probably the best described Arawak language by far, with its reference grammar [#tariana] being over 600 pages long. This means that I will have to limit my description to the most salient aspects.

Tariana is one of the few Arawak languages with core case marking; this is probably due to influence from the neighbouring Tucanoan languages. This means that a discussion of split intransitivity will have to consider case marking in addition to verbal cross-referencing (and word order).

The situation with respect to verbal marking is easier. Arawak suffixes are lost in Tariana and only the prefixes remain. A arguments are cross-referenced by prefixes, while P arguments are not marked at all on the verb, as shown by the transitive verb *-inu*, 'kill':

